fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
For the first claim, we need a functor L such that arrows from L(GFA \xrightarrow{\alpha} A) to X is in bijection with commutative squares
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin{tikzcd} GFA & GFGX \\ A & GX \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow["{\alpha}"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["{G \epsilon}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2] \end{tikzcd}
which are equivalent by F \dashv G to the commutative squares
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin{tikzcd} FGFA & FGX \\ FA & X \arrow["FG\varphi", from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow["F\alpha"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\epsilon", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \end{tikzcd}
Further notice that \epsilon \mathbin{\circ} FG\varphi = \varphi \mathbin{\circ} \epsilon by naturality. So it becomes obvious that L should be defined as the coequalizer of the pair F \alpha, \epsilon : FGFA \rightrightarrows FA. This is reflexive by the common section F\eta.

For the second point, we unfold the unit as a natural family of commutative squares



        \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

  \begin{tikzcd}
  GFA & {GFG\operatorname*{colim}(FGFA \rightrightarrows FA)} \\
  A & {G\operatorname*{colim}(FGFA \rightrightarrows FA)}
  \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
  \arrow[from=1-1, to=2-1]
  \arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
  \arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2]
\end{tikzcd}



and when G preserves the coequalizers in the diagram, the problem is reduced to showing that the coequalizer of GF\alpha and G\epsilon : GFGFA \rightrightarrows GFA is isomorphic to A via the bottom map, which is just the unit \eta : A \to GFA composed with the coequalizing map. This is a routine diagram chase.
